msgid "Declarative shell environments with `shell.nix`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:10
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:12
msgid "Declarative shell environments allow you to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:14
msgid "Automatically run bash commands during environment activation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:15
msgid "Automatically set environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:16
msgid ""
"Put the environment definition under version control and reproduce it on "
"other machines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:18
msgid "What will you learn?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:20
msgid ""
"In the {ref}`ad-hoc-envs` tutorial, you learned how to imperatively create "
"shell environments using `nix-shell -p`. This is great when you want to "
"quickly access tools without installing them permanently. You also learned "
"how to execute that command with a specific Nixpkgs revision using a Git "
"commit as an argument, to recreate the same environment used previously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:24
msgid ""
"In this tutorial we'll take a look at how to create reproducible shell "
"environments with a declarative configuration in a {term}`Nix file`. This "
"file can be shared with anyone to recreate the same environment on a "
"different machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:27
msgid "How long will it take?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:29
msgid "30 minutes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:31
msgid "What do you need?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:33
msgid "Familiarity with the Unix shell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:34
msgid "A rudimentary understanding of the [Nix language](reading-nix-language)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:36
msgid "Entering a temporary shell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:38
msgid ""
"Suppose we want an environment where `cowsay` and `lolcat` are available. "
"The simplest possible way to accomplish this is via the `nix-shell -p` "
"command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:41
msgid "$ nix-shell -p cowsay lolcat\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:45
msgid "This command works, but there's a number of drawbacks:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:46
msgid "You have to type out `-p cowsay lolcat` every time you enter the shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:47
msgid ""
"It doesn't (ergonomically) allow you any further customization of your shell "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:49
msgid ""
"A better solution is to create our shell environment from a `shell.nix` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:51
msgid "A basic `shell.nix` file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:53
msgid "Create a file called `shell.nix` with these contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:56
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-24.05\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
"\n"
"pkgs.mkShellNoCC {\n"
"  packages = with pkgs; [\n"
"    cowsay\n"
"    lolcat\n"
"  ];\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:0
msgid "Detailed explanation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:71
msgid ""
"We use a version of [Nixpkgs pinned to a release branch](<ref-pinning-"
"nixpkgs>). If you followed the [](ad-hoc-envs) tutorial and don't want to "
"download all dependencies again, specify the exact same revision as in the "
"section [](towards-reproducibility):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:75
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/"
"tarball/2a601aafdc5605a5133a2ca506a34a3a73377247\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:82
msgid ""
"We explicitly set `config` and `overlays` to avoid them being inadvertently "
"overridden by [global configuration](https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/"
"#chap-packageconfig)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:84
msgid ""
"`mkShellNoCC` is a function that takes as an argument an attribute set. Here "
"we give it an attribute `packages` with a list containing two items from the "
"`pkgs` attribute set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:0
msgid "Side note on `mkShell`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:89
msgid ""
"`nix-shell` and `mkShell` were originally conceived as a way to construct a "
"shell environment containing the [tools needed to debug package builds]"
"(https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/#sec-tools-of-stdenv), such as Make "
"or GCC. Only later did it become widely used as a general way to make "
"temporary environments for other purposes. `mkShellNoCC` is a function that "
"produces such an environment, but without a compiler toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:93
msgid ""
"You may encounter examples of `mkShell` or `mkShellNoCC` that add packages "
"to the `buildInputs` or `nativeBuildInputs` attributes instead. "
"`mkShellNoCC` is a [wrapper around `mkDerivation`](https://nixos.org/manual/"
"nixpkgs/stable/#sec-pkgs-mkShell), so it takes the same arguments as "
"`mkDerivation`, such as `buildInputs` or `nativeBuildInputs`. The `packages` "
"attribute argument to `mkShellNoCC` is simply an alias for "
"`nativeBuildInputs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:99
msgid ""
"Enter the environment by running `nix-shell` in the same directory as `shell."
"nix`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:102
msgid ""
"The first invocation of `nix-shell` on this file may take a while to "
"download all dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:105
msgid ""
"$ nix-shell\n"
"[nix-shell]$ cowsay hello | lolcat\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:110
msgid ""
"`nix-shell` by default looks for a file called `shell.nix` in the current "
"directory and builds a shell environment from the Nix expression in this "
"file. Packages defined in the `packages` attribute will be available in "
"`$PATH`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:113
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:115
msgid ""
"You may want to automatically export certain environment variables when you "
"enter a shell environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:117
msgid "Set `GREETING` so it can be used in the shell environment:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:119
msgid ""
" let\n"
"   nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-24.05\";\n"
"   pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
" in\n"
"\n"
" pkgs.mkShellNoCC {\n"
"   packages = with pkgs; [\n"
"     cowsay\n"
"     lolcat\n"
"   ];\n"
"\n"
"+  GREETING = \"Hello, Nix!\";\n"
" }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:135
msgid ""
"Any attribute name passed to `mkShellNoCC` that is not reserved otherwise "
"and has a value which can be coerced to a string will end up as an "
"environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:137
msgid ""
"Try it out! Exit the shell by typing `exit` or pressing `Ctrl`+`D`, then "
"start it again with `nix-shell`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:140
msgid "[nix-shell]$ echo $GREETING\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:145
msgid "Some variables are protected from being set as described above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:147
msgid ""
"For example, the shell prompt format for most shells is set by the `PS1` "
"environment variable, but `nix-shell` already sets this by default, and will "
"ignore a `PS1` attribute set in the argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:149
msgid ""
"If you need to override these protected environment variables, use the "
"`shellHook` attribute as described in the next section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:152
msgid "Startup commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:154
msgid ""
"You may want to run some commands before entering the shell environment. "
"These commands can be placed in the `shellHook` attribute provided to "
"`mkShellNoCC`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:157
msgid "Set `shellHook` to output a colorful greeting:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:159
msgid ""
" let\n"
"   nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-24.05\";\n"
"   pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
" in\n"
"\n"
" pkgs.mkShellNoCC {\n"
"   packages = with pkgs; [\n"
"     cowsay\n"
"     lolcat\n"
"   ];\n"
"\n"
"   GREETING = \"Hello, Nix!\";\n"
"+\n"
"+  shellHook = ''\n"
"+    echo $GREETING | cowsay | lolcat\n"
"+  '';\n"
" }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/first-steps/declarative-shell.md:179
msgid ""
"Try it again! Exit the shell by typing `exit` or pressing `Ctrl`+`D`, then "
"start it again with `nix-shell` to observe the effect."
msgstr ""

